From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia

Taxonomic rank between class and family

This article is about the taxonomic rank. For the sequence of species in a taxonomic list, see [taxonomic sequence](/wiki/Taxonomic_sequence "Taxonomic sequence"). For other uses, see [Order](/wiki/Order_(disambiguation) "Order (disambiguation)").

[![](//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a5/Biological_classification_L_Pengo_vflip.svg/150px-Biological_classification_L_Pengo_vflip.svg.png)](/wiki/File:Biological_classification_L_Pengo_vflip.svg "File:Biological classification L Pengo vflip.svg")

*The hierarchy of [biological classification](/wiki/Taxonomy_(biology) "Taxonomy (biology)")'s eight major [taxonomic ranks](/wiki/Taxonomic_rank "Taxonomic rank"). A [class](/wiki/Class_(biology) "Class (biology)") contains one or more orders. Intermediate minor rankings are not shown.*

**Order** ([Latin](/wiki/Latin_language "Latin language"): *[ordo](https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/ordo#Latin "wikt:ordo")*) is one of the eight major [hierarchical](/wiki/Hierarchical "Hierarchical") taxonomic ranks in [Linnaean taxonomy](/wiki/Linnaean_taxonomy "Linnaean taxonomy"). It is classified between [family](/wiki/Family_(biology) "Family (biology)") and [class](/wiki/Class_(biology) "Class (biology)"). In [biological classification](/wiki/Biological_classification "Biological classification"), the order is a [taxonomic rank](/wiki/Taxonomic_rank "Taxonomic rank") used in the classification of organisms and recognized by the [nomenclature codes](/wiki/Nomenclature_codes "Nomenclature codes"). An immediately higher rank, **superorder**, is sometimes added directly above order, with **suborder** directly beneath order. An order can also be defined as a group of related families.

What does and does not belong to each order is determined by a [taxonomist](/wiki/Taxonomist "Taxonomist"), as is whether a particular order should be recognized at all. Often there is no exact agreement, with different taxonomists each taking a different position. There are no hard rules that a taxonomist needs to follow in describing or recognizing an order. Some taxa are accepted almost universally, while others are recognized only rarely.[[1]](#cite_note-1)

The name of an order is usually written with a capital letter.[[2]](#cite_note-2) For some groups of organisms, their orders may follow consistent naming [schemes](/wiki/Classification_scheme_(information_science) "Classification scheme (information science)"). Orders of [plants](/wiki/Plant "Plant"), [fungi](/wiki/Fungi "Fungi"), and [algae](/wiki/Alga "Alga") use the suffix *-ales* (e.g. [Dictyotales](/wiki/Dictyotales "Dictyotales")).[[3]](#cite_note-3) Orders of [birds](/wiki/Bird "Bird") and [fishes](/wiki/Fish "Fish")[[4]](#cite_note-Berg1940-4) use the Latin suffix *-iformes* meaning 'having the form of' (e.g. [Passeriformes](/wiki/Passeriformes "Passeriformes")), but orders of [mammals](/wiki/Mammal "Mammal"), [reptiles](/wiki/Reptile "Reptile"), [amphibians](/wiki/Amphibia "Amphibia") and [invertebrates](/wiki/Invertebrate "Invertebrate") are not so consistent (e.g. [Artiodactyla](/wiki/Artiodactyla "Artiodactyla"), [Anura](/wiki/Frog "Frog"), [Crocodylia](/wiki/Crocodylia "Crocodylia"), [Actiniaria](/wiki/Actiniaria "Actiniaria"), [Primates](/wiki/Primates "Primates")).

## Hierarchy of ranks

[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Order_(biology)&action=edit&section=1 "Edit section: Hierarchy of ranks")]

### Zoology

[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Order_(biology)&action=edit&section=2 "Edit section: Zoology")]

For some [clades](/wiki/Clade "Clade") covered by the [International Code of Zoological Nomenclature](/wiki/International_Code_of_Zoological_Nomenclature "International Code of Zoological Nomenclature"), several additional classifications are sometimes used, although not all of these are officially recognized.

| Name | Latin [prefix](/wiki/Prefix "Prefix") | Examples |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Magnorder | *[magnus](https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/magnus#Latin "wikt:magnus")*, 'large, great, important' | [Boreoeutheria](/wiki/Boreoeutheria "Boreoeutheria") |
| Superorder | *[super](https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/super#Latin "wikt:super")*, 'above' | [Euarchontoglires](/wiki/Euarchontoglires "Euarchontoglires"), [Laurasiatheria](/wiki/Laurasiatheria "Laurasiatheria") |
| Grandorder | *[grandis](https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/grandis#Latin "wikt:grandis")*, 'large' | [Euarchonta](/wiki/Euarchonta "Euarchonta"), [Ferungulata](/wiki/Ferungulata "Ferungulata") |
| Mirorder | *[mirus](https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/mirus#Latin "wikt:mirus")*, 'wonderful, strange' | [Primatomorpha](/wiki/Primatomorpha "Primatomorpha"), [Ferae](/wiki/Ferae "Ferae") |
| Order |  | [Primates](/wiki/Primate "Primate"), [Procolophonomorpha](/wiki/Procolophonomorpha "Procolophonomorpha") |
| Suborder | *[sub](https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/sub#Latin "wikt:sub")*, 'under' | [Haplorrhini](/wiki/Haplorrhini "Haplorrhini"), [Procolophonia](/wiki/Procolophonia "Procolophonia") |
| Infraorder | *[infra](https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/infra#Latin "wikt:infra")*, 'below' | [Simiiformes](/wiki/Simiiformes "Simiiformes"), [Tarsiiformes](/wiki/Tarsiiformes "Tarsiiformes") |
| Parvorder | *[parvus](https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/parvus#Latin "wikt:parvus")*, 'small, unimportant' | [Catarrhini](/wiki/Catarrhini "Catarrhini"), [Mysticeti](/wiki/Baleen_whale "Baleen whale") |


In their 1997 classification of [mammals](/wiki/Mammal "Mammal"), [McKenna](/wiki/Malcolm_McKenna "Malcolm McKenna") and Bell used two extra levels between superorder and order: *grandorder* and *mirorder*.[[5]](#cite_note-McKennaBell1997-5) Michael Novacek (1986) inserted them at the same position. [Michael Benton](/wiki/Michael_Benton "Michael Benton") (2005) inserted them between superorder and magnorder instead.[[6]](#cite_note-MichaelJBenton2005_VPalaentology_3rd-6) This position was adopted by *Systema Naturae 2000* and others.

### Botany

[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Order_(biology)&action=edit&section=3 "Edit section: Botany")]

In [botany](/wiki/Botany "Botany"), the ranks of subclass and suborder are secondary ranks pre-defined as respectively above and below the rank of order.[[7]](#cite_note-botarticle4-7) Any number of further ranks can be used as long as they are clearly defined.[[7]](#cite_note-botarticle4-7)

The superorder rank is commonly used, with the ending *-anae* that was initiated by [Armen Takhtajan](/wiki/Armen_Takhtajan "Armen Takhtajan")'s publications from 1966 onwards.[[8]](#cite_note-8)

## History

[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Order_(biology)&action=edit&section=4 "Edit section: History")]

The order as a distinct rank of biological classification having its own distinctive name (and not just called a *higher genus* (*genus summum*)) was first introduced by the German botanist [Augustus Quirinus Rivinus](/wiki/Augustus_Quirinus_Rivinus "Augustus Quirinus Rivinus") in his classification of plants that appeared in a series of treatises in the 1690s. [Carl Linnaeus](/wiki/Carl_Linnaeus "Carl Linnaeus") was the first to apply it consistently to the division of all three kingdoms of nature (then [minerals](/wiki/Mineral "Mineral"), [plants](/wiki/Plant "Plant"), and [animals](/wiki/Animal "Animal")) in his *[Systema Naturae](/wiki/Systema_Naturae "Systema Naturae")* (1735, 1st. Ed.).

### Botany

[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Order_(biology)&action=edit&section=5 "Edit section: Botany")]

[![](//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/ae/Linnaeus1758-title-page.jpg/250px-Linnaeus1758-title-page.jpg)](/wiki/File:Linnaeus1758-title-page.jpg)

*Title page of the 1758 edition of Linnaeus's *Systema Naturæ*.[[9]](#cite_note-Linn1758-9)*

For plants, Linnaeus' orders in the *Systema Naturae* and the *[Species Plantarum](/wiki/Species_Plantarum "Species Plantarum")* were strictly artificial, introduced to subdivide the artificial classes into more comprehensible smaller groups. When the word *ordo* was first consistently used for natural units of plants, in 19th-century works such as the *[Prodromus Systematis Naturalis Regni Vegetabilis](/wiki/Prodromus_Systematis_Naturalis_Regni_Vegetabilis "Prodromus Systematis Naturalis Regni Vegetabilis")* of [Augustin Pyramus de Candolle](/wiki/Augustin_Pyramus_de_Candolle "Augustin Pyramus de Candolle") and the *[Genera Plantarum](/wiki/Bentham_%26_Hooker_system "Bentham &amp; Hooker system")* of Bentham & Hooker, it indicated taxa that are now given the rank of family (see [ordo naturalis](/wiki/Ordo_naturalis "Ordo naturalis"), '*natural order*').

In French botanical publications, from [Michel Adanson](/wiki/Michel_Adanson "Michel Adanson")'s *Familles naturelles des plantes* (1763) and until the end of the 19th century, the word *famille* (plural: *familles*) was used as a French equivalent for this Latin *ordo*. This equivalence was explicitly stated in the [Alphonse Pyramus de Candolle](/wiki/Alphonse_Pyramus_de_Candolle "Alphonse Pyramus de Candolle")'s *Lois de la nomenclature botanique* (1868), the precursor of the currently used *[International Code of Nomenclature for algae, fungi, and plants](/wiki/International_Code_of_Nomenclature_for_algae,_fungi,_and_plants "International Code of Nomenclature for algae, fungi, and plants")*.

In the first international *Rules* of [botanical nomenclature](/wiki/Botanical_nomenclature "Botanical nomenclature") from the [International Botanical Congress](/wiki/International_Botanical_Congress "International Botanical Congress") of 1905, the word *family* (*familia*) was assigned to the rank indicated by the French *famille*, while order (*ordo*) was reserved for a higher rank, for what in the 19th century had often been named a 'cohort' (*cohors*,[[10]](#cite_note-10) plural *cohortes*).

Some of the plant families still retain the names of Linnaean "natural orders" or even the names of pre-Linnaean natural groups recognized by Linnaeus as orders in his natural classification (e.g. *[Palmae](/wiki/Palmae "Palmae")* or *[Labiatae](/wiki/Labiatae "Labiatae")*). Such names are known as [descriptive](/wiki/Descriptive_botanical_name "Descriptive botanical name") family names.

### Zoology

[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Order_(biology)&action=edit&section=6 "Edit section: Zoology")]

In the field of [zoology](/wiki/Zoology "Zoology"), the Linnaean orders were used more consistently. That is, the orders in the zoology part of the *Systema Naturae* refer to natural groups. Some of his ordinal names are still in use, e.g. [Lepidoptera](/wiki/Lepidoptera "Lepidoptera") (moths and butterflies) and [Diptera](/wiki/Diptera "Diptera") (flies, mosquitoes, midges, and gnats).[[11]](#cite_note-General2-11)

### Virology

[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Order_(biology)&action=edit&section=7 "Edit section: Virology")]

In [virology](/wiki/Virology "Virology"), the [International Committee on Taxonomy of Viruses](/wiki/International_Committee_on_Taxonomy_of_Viruses "International Committee on Taxonomy of Viruses")'s [virus classification](/wiki/Virus_classification "Virus classification") includes fifteen taxonomic ranks to be applied for [viruses](/wiki/Virus "Virus"), [viroids](/wiki/Viroid "Viroid") and [satellite nucleic acids](/wiki/Satellite_(biology) "Satellite (biology)"): [realm](/wiki/Realm_(virology) "Realm (virology)"), [subrealm](/wiki/Realm_(virology)#Subrealm "Realm (virology)"), [kingdom](/wiki/Kingdom_(biology) "Kingdom (biology)"), subkingdom, [phylum](/wiki/Phylum "Phylum"), [subphylum](/wiki/Subphylum "Subphylum"), class, subclass, order, suborder, family, [subfamily](/wiki/Subfamily "Subfamily"), genus, [subgenus](/wiki/Subgenus "Subgenus"), and species.[[12]](#cite_note-ICTV_2018-12) There are currently fourteen viral orders, each ending in the suffix *-virales*.[[13]](#cite_note-13)

